{
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "A subordinate clause that functions as a noun within a larger sentence. Often introduced by que and can act as subject, object, or object of a preposition.",
      "title": "Noun Clause: Definition"
    },
    {
      "description": "A clause serving as the direct object of a main verb. Example: Quiero que vengas.",
      "title": "Noun Clause: Direct Object Position"
    },
    {
      "description": "A clause functioning as the subject, common with impersonal expressions. Example: Es importante que estudies.",
      "title": "Noun Clause: Subject Position"
    },
    {
      "description": "A clause introduced after a preposition in the main phrase, typically with de que. Example: Me alegro de que estés aquí.",
      "title": "Noun Clause: After Prepositions"
    },
    {
      "description": "Que introduces the subordinate noun clause after a triggering main clause. It connects the two clauses without a comma in Spanish.",
      "title": "Que as Subordinator"
    },
    {
      "description": "Use the subjunctive in the noun clause when the subject differs from the main clause subject. Example: Ella quiere que tú vayas.",
      "title": "Change of Subject Rule"
    },
    {
      "description": "Use an infinitive if there is no subject change instead of a subjunctive clause. Example: Ella quiere ir.",
      "title": "Same Subject: Infinitive Instead"
    },
    {
      "description": "When the main clause is in present or future, use present subjunctive in the noun clause. Example: Espero que vengas mañana.",
      "title": "Present Main Verb: Present Subjunctive"
    },
    {
      "description": "With a past or conditional main verb, use imperfect subjunctive in the noun clause. Example: Quería que vinieras.",
      "title": "Past or Conditional Main Verb: Imperfect Subjunctive"
    },
    {
      "description": "Use haya + participle when the noun clause action occurs before the main clause. Example: Me alegra que hayas llegado.",
      "title": "Earlier Action: Present Perfect Subjunctive"
    },
    {
      "description": "Use hubiera/hubiese + participle for an action earlier than a past main verb. Example: Me alegraba que hubieras llegado.",
      "title": "Earlier Action with Past Main Verb: Pluperfect Subjunctive"
    },
    {
      "description": "When the main clause expresses certainty, the noun clause takes the indicative, not the subjunctive.",
      "title": "Certainty Blocks Subjunctive"
    },
    {
      "description": "Willing that someone else do something triggers the subjunctive. Example: Quiero que él llame.",
      "title": "Querer que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Wishing that another person act triggers the subjunctive. Example: Deseo que tengas suerte.",
      "title": "Desear que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Stating a preference for another’s action triggers the subjunctive. Example: Prefiero que conduzcas tú.",
      "title": "Preferir que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Hoping for another’s action triggers the subjunctive. Example: Espero que llegues a tiempo.",
      "title": "Esperar que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Needing someone else to do something triggers the subjunctive. Example: Necesito que me ayudes.",
      "title": "Necesitar que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Requesting that someone do something triggers the subjunctive. Example: Le pido que firme.",
      "title": "Pedir que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Begging someone to do something triggers the subjunctive. Example: Te ruego que vuelvas.",
      "title": "Rogar que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Pleading for someone to act triggers the subjunctive. Example: Suplico que me escuchen.",
      "title": "Suplicar que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Insisting that another person act triggers the subjunctive. Example: Insisto en que salgas ahora.",
      "title": "Insistir en que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Demanding an action from someone triggers the subjunctive. Example: Exijo que me expliquen.",
      "title": "Exigir que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Ordering someone to do something triggers the subjunctive. Example: Mando que lo hagan hoy.",
      "title": "Mandar que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Issuing an order triggers the subjunctive. Example: Ordeno que abran la puerta.",
      "title": "Ordenar que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Forbidding someone from doing something triggers the subjunctive. Example: Prohíbo que fumen aquí.",
      "title": "Prohibir que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Allowing someone to do something triggers the subjunctive. Example: Permito que salgas temprano.",
      "title": "Permitir que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Letting someone do something triggers the subjunctive. Example: Dejo que él decida.",
      "title": "Dejar que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Suggesting an action to another triggers the subjunctive. Example: Sugiero que estudien más.",
      "title": "Sugerir que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Recommending that someone act triggers the subjunctive. Example: Recomiendo que lleguen temprano.",
      "title": "Recomendar que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Advising someone to act triggers the subjunctive. Example: Aconsejo que descanses.",
      "title": "Aconsejar que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Causing someone to do something triggers the subjunctive. Example: Hago que él trabaje más.",
      "title": "Hacer que"
    },
    {
      "description": "Using decir to tell someone to do something triggers the subjunctive. Example: Le digo que se siente.",
      "title": "Decir que as a Command"
    },
    {
      "description": "Reporting what someone said takes the indicative, not the subjunctive. Example: Dice que viene a las cinco.",
      "title": "Decir que to Report Information"
